'''Abu'l-Aswar''' or '''Abu'l-Asvar Shavur ibn Fadl ibn Muhammad ibn Shaddad''' was a member of the [[Shaddadid dynasty]]. Between 1049 and 1067 he was the eighth Shaddadid ruler of [[Arran (Caucasus)|Arran]] (today in western [[Azerbaijan]]) from [[Ganja, Azerbaijan|Ganja]]. Prior to that, he ruled the city of [[Dvin (ancient city)|Dvin]] (in what is now [[Armenia]] and northeastern [[Turkey]]) from 1022 as an autonomous lord. A capable warrior, and a wise and cunning ruler, Abu'l-Aswar was engaged in several conflicts with most of his neighbours. During his rule over Dvin, he was mostly involved in the affairs of the [[Medieval Armenia|Armenian]] principalities. He collaborated with the [[Byzantine Empire]] in its conquest of the last remnants of [[Bagratid Armenia]] in 1045, but when the Byzantines later turned on him, he survived three successive offensives that sought to take Ganja. In 1049, a revolt in Ganja overthrew his infant great-great-nephew, [[Anushirvan ibn Lashkari|Anurshirvan]]. The rebels invited him to take up the family's emirate, and he moved from Dvin to Ganja. Under his rule, the Shaddadid dynasty reached its zenith. He undertook successful campaigns into [[Kingdom of Georgia|Georgia]] and [[Shirvan]], although the limits of Shaddadid power were exposed by his failure to take over the [[Emirate of Tiflis]] and by devastating raids by the [[Alans]]. At the same time, his reign witnessed the rapid rise of the [[Seljuk Empire]] and the extension of its control over the [[Transcaucasia]]n principalities. Abu'l-Aswar became a Seljuk [[vassal]] in 1054/5. Although he gained control over the former Armenian capital of [[Ani]] through Seljuk patronage in 1065, this association also paved the way for the dynasty's decline after his death in November 1067.

== Biography ==
=== Origin ===
The main historical source on the [[Shaddadids]] is the work of the [[Ottoman Turks|Ottoman]] historian [[Münejjim Bashi]] (died 1702).{{sfn|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|p=119}}{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|pp=2–4}} Münejjim Bashi considered the family to be of [[Kurds|Kurdish]] origin, a view widely accepted by modern scholars.{{sfn|Peacock|2011}}{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|pp=33–34}}{{sfn|Bosworth|1968|p=34}} The family's founder, [[Muhammad ibn Shaddad]], briefly seized control of [[Dvin (ancient city)|Dvin]] in the early 950s. The family then moved to [[Ganja, Azerbaijan|Ganja]], the main Muslim town of [[Arran (Caucasus)|Arran]], which was seized by Muhammad's sons [[Lashkari ibn Muhammad|Lashkari (I)]], [[Marzuban ibn Muhammad (Shaddadid)|Marzuban]], and [[al-Fadl ibn Muhammad|Fadl (I)]] {{circa|970}}. The brothers successively ruled the city as emirs after that.{{sfn|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|p=119}}{{sfn|Peacock|2011}}{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|pp=5–16, 34–39}} Abu'l-Aswar Shavur was the second son of the youngest of the three brothers, and fourth Shaddadid ruler, Fadl. In his long reign (985–1031), Fadl expanded the family's control over much of Arran as well as parts of [[Medieval Armenia|Armenia]], capturing [[Syunik Province|Syunik]].{{sfn|Peacock|2011}}{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|pp=6, 16–17, 40–45}} Fadl was succeeded as emir at Ganja by his eldest son Musa ({{reign|1031|1034}}) who was in turn murdered by his own son [[Lashkari ibn Musa|Abu'l-Hasan Lashkari (II)]] ({{reign|1034|1049}}).{{sfn|Peacock|2011}}{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|pp=6, 17–18, 46–50}} Abu'l-Aswar Shavur's name is an Arabic–Persian hybrid: "Shavur" is the old Persian name "[[Shapur (name)|Shapur]]", while his ''[[kunya (Arabic)|kunya]]'' contains the Arabicized form of the Iranian (possibly [[Daylamite]]) name "Asvar" (cognate with ''savar'', "horseman, knight").{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|p=50}}

=== Lord of Dvin (1022–49) ===
[[File:Caucasus 1060 map en.svg|thumb|right|250px|alt=Map of the Caucasus region with the various principalities in different colours|Political map of the Caucasus region {{circa|1060}}]]
Münejjim Bashi records that at the time of his death in 1067, Abu'l-Aswar's total reign, both in Ganja and before that "over some territories", had lasted 46 years. "Some territories" clearly refers to his rule over Dvin, known from other sources, meaning that he became ruler of the city in {{circa|1022}}.{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|p=22}}{{sfn|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|pp=120–121}} The city, although part of the [[Bagratid Kingdom of Armenia]], had been left defenceless after the death of [[Gagik I of Armenia]] in 1020 and the dispute of his sons over their inheritance, and suffered a devastating Daylamite raid in 1021 which effectively cut it off from the remainder of the Armenian kingdom. In the aftermath, the city appears to have sought the protection of the Shaddadids, and Abu'l-Aswar became its ruler.{{sfn|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|p=120}} From this base, he pursued a virtually independent course from his brother, and later his nephew, in Ganja, focused more on Armenia than Arran.{{sfn|Peacock|2011}}{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|p=44}} Abu'l-Aswar was intimately connected with the Armenian princely houses, having married a sister of [[David I Anhoghin]], [[Kingdom of Tashir-Dzoraget|King of Tashir]]. His [[Ashot ibn Shavur|second son]] even bore the typically Armenian name of Ashot.{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|p=51}} Due to his focus on the affairs of his domain, he is not mentioned by Münejjim Bashi until his takeover of the main family seat at Ganja in 1049. For his activities in the period 1022–49, the main sources derive from his opponents, the Armenians and the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantines]].{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|p=50}}

Abu'l-Aswar is first recorded by the history of [[Matthew of Edessa]] in 1040, when the Armenian nobleman Abirat, who had become embroiled in the dispute between Gagik I's sons [[Ashot IV]] and [[Hovhannes-Smbat III of Armenia|Hovhannes-Smbat III]], came to Dvin. Fearful of the latter's displeasure, Abirat with 12,000 horsemen sought Abu'l-Aswar's protection. Abu'l-Aswar initially welcomed Abirat and gave him a high position, but soon came to mistrust him, and had him killed, whereupon Abirat's lieutenant Sare departed for [[Ani]] with Abirat's supporters.{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|p=51}}{{sfn|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|p=121}} Despite their kinship, at about the same time Abu'l-Aswar attacked David of Tashir. The Shaddadid army, numbering an impossible 150,000 according to Matthew of Edessa, captured much of Tashir, but David was able to assemble a broad alliance against Abu'l-Aswar. David himself fielded 10,000 troops, Hovhannes-Smbat III of Ani sent 3,000 men, the [[Kingdom of Artsakh|King of Kapan]] sent 2,000, and even the [[Kingdom of Georgia|King of Georgia]] sent 4,000, while David also secured the public backing of the [[Church of Caucasian Albania|Catholicos of Albania]]. As a result, Abu'l-Aswar was defeated and evicted from Tashir.{{sfn|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|p=121}}{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|pp=51–52}}

Ashot IV and Hovhannes-Smbat III died at almost the same time ({{circa|1040/41}}), and Ashot's son [[Gagik II of Armenia|Gagik II]] ({{reign|1042|1045}}) succeeded them both and began consolidating his position. The chief danger to his throne was the Byzantine Empire, which throughout the early 11th century had been encroaching on the Armenian principalities. Hovhannes-Smbat had even bequeathed his kingdom to the Empire, and after his death, Emperor [[Michael IV the Paphlagonian]] ({{reign|1034|1041}}) sent troops to capture Ani. Gagik managed to repel the attack, and political turmoil in Constantinople gained him a couple of years of reprieve after that, but in 1042 a new emperor, [[Constantine IX Monomachos]] ({{reign|1042|1055}}), came to the throne determined to secure Byzantine claims in Armenia.{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|p=52}}{{sfn|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|pp=121–122}} 

[[File:The Byzantines are defeated by Aplesphares.jpg|thumb|left|250px|alt=Medieval illuminated miniature showing one group of horsemen pursuing another, with fallen soldiers at their feet|The defeat of the Byzantines before Dvin, miniature from the ''[[Madrid Skylitzes]]'']]
To this end, he contacted Abu'l-Aswar and called upon him to attack the Armenians from the rear. Abu'l-Aswar agreed, in exchange for guarantees that he would retain his conquests, a request granted in an imperial [[chrysobull]]. Faced with a two-pronged assault, Gagik was forced to visit Constantinople. There he was kept hostage and Ani was surrendered to the Byzantines in 1045.{{sfn|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|p=122}}{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|pp=52–53}} Notwithstanding his previous promises, immediately after taking possession of Ani, the emperor requested that Abu'l-Aswar vacate the fortresses he had conquered. When the latter refused, a large army under [[Michael Iasites]] and the ''[[magistros]]'' [[Constantine the Alan]], containing numerous Armenians, marched against Dvin. Abu'l-Aswar let them approach, and then opened the irrigation canals and flooded the plain around the city. Stuck in the mud, the besiegers were easy prey for the Shaddadid archers, who inflicted huge casualties on the Byzantine force.{{sfn|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|p=122}}{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|p=53}} Constantine IX responded by placing [[Katakalon Kekaumenos]] and the ''[[parakoimomenos]]'' Constantine in charge of Armenia. Instead of attacking Dvin, however, the new Byzantine leadership concentrated its efforts on recovering the forts captured by Abu'l-Aswar. [[Surmari]], [[Anberd]], and [[Khor Virap]] fell to the Byzantine army, but Chelidonion (modern [[Yerevan]]) resisted until September 1047, when the outbreak of a rebellion led by [[Leo Tornikios]] forced the army's recall to Constantinople. A peace treaty was hastily concluded, whereby Abu'l-Aswar agreed not to raid Byzantine territory and to recognize the authority of the emperor.{{sfn|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|pp=122–123}}{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|pp=53–54}}

The successful resistance of Dvin put an end to the Byzantine advance in Armenia, helping preserve the independence of the smaller Armenian realms of Syunik, Tashir and [[Principality of Khachen|Khachen]].{{sfn|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|p=123}} Soon after, the regional balance of power was permanently altered with the [[Battle of Kapetron|first large-scale raid]] of the [[Seljuk Turks]] under [[Qutlumush ibn Arslan Isra'il]] and [[Ibrahim Inal]] into Byzantine Armenia in 1048.{{sfn|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|p=123}} While the Shaddadids may have been tempted to see in them welcome allies against the Byzantines,{{sfn|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|p=123}} they were equally likely to be a threat, as demonstrated by the attack on Ganja by Qutlumush in 1046/47.{{sfn|Bosworth|1968|p=34}}{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|pp=18, 48}}

Shortly after, in late 1048 or early 1049—although some authors have suggested a later date, {{circa|1050}} ([[August Friedrich Gfrörer|A.F. Gfrörer]] and M.H. Yinanç) or even {{circa|1055/56}} (E. Honigmann){{sfn|Minorsky|1977|pp=55, 60–61}}—the Byzantines launched another offensive against Dvin under the ''[[rhaiktor]]'' Nikephoros. According to the contemporary Byzantine historian [[John Skylitzes]], this was because Abu'l-Aswar ("Aplesphares", as the Byzantines called him) had violated the previous agreement and raided Byzantine lands. The Shaddadid ruler remained ensconced in Dvin, while the Byzantines devastated its environs "as far as the Iron Bridge and Ganja", forcing Abu'l-Aswar to renew his previous oath of subservience and hand over his great-nephew Ardashir, the son of Abu'l-Hasan Lashkari, as a hostage.{{sfn|Bosworth|1968|p=34}}{{sfn|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|p=123}}{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|pp=48–49, 54–56, 59–64}}

=== Emir of Ganja (1049–67) ===
In 1049, Abu'l-Aswar's nephew Lashkari, the emir of Ganja, died, after a troubled reign of 15 years. He was succeeded by his infant son [[Anushirvan ibn Lashkari|Anushirvan]], but actual power was in the hands of his chamberlain (''[[hajib]]''), Abu Mansur. After barely two months, a group of elders opposed to the new regime's policies deposed Abu Mansur while he was at [[Shamkur]] and called upon Abu'l-Aswar to assume control of Ganja as well.{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|pp=18–19}} Abu'l-Aswar agreed and abandoned Dvin, which had become too exposed to the Byzantines. The city was left in the hands of a series of governors until 1053, when he appointed his son Abu Nasr Iskandar as ruler of the city and the surrounding regions.{{sfn|Ter-Ghewondyan|1976|p=123}} The Shaddadid ruler first set things in order in Shamkur, and then entered Ganja, taking possession "all the lands of Arran and its fortresses".{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|p=19}}

At this point in his career, Abu'l-Aswar had achieved a considerable reputation as a ruler and a warrior; the [[Ziyarid]] prince [[Keikavus]] ({{reign|1050|1087}}), who later wrote a well-known [[mirror for princes]], the ''[[Qabusnameh]]'', even came to Ganja and spent several years at the Shaddadid court to participate in the ''[[jihad]]'' against the Christians, after having spent eight years at the court of [[Maw'dud of Ghazni]].{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|p=56}}{{sfn|Bosworth|1968|p=35}} According to Keikavus, his host was "a great king, a man firm and clever, [...] just, courageous, eloquent dialectician, of pure faith and far-sighted".{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|p=56}} This estimate was shared by the Byzantines, for Skylitzes likewise calls him "as clever a strategist as anybody else, capable of thwarting the enemies' tactics and policies",{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|p=56}} while Münejjim Bashi writes that after his takeover of Ganja, "Abu'l-Aswar [...] restored the name of the dynasty to life after it had nearly died out. He became strong and the situation of the subjects and the army became orderly."{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|p=19}}

[[File:Gates gelati.jpg|thumb|right|250px|alt=Photograph of an iron-covered door with Arabic inscriptions in two bands across it|The [[gates of Ganja]], installed under Abu'l-Aswar's orders in 1062, now at the [[Gelati Monastery]] in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]]]
According to Münejjim Bashi, in 1053, Abu'l-Aswar seized the (unidentified) fortress of Basra from the Georgians, and refortified and garrisoned it with many men.{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|p=19}} In 1054/5, along with many of the neighbouring rulers, he became a vassal of the Seljuk Sultan [[Toghrul Beg]] ({{reign|1037|1063}}), although at least initially the impact of Seljuk overlordship seems to have been light, as neither Toghrul nor his successor [[Alp Arslan]] ({{reign|1063|1072}}) appeared on Shaddadid coinage at this time.{{sfn|Peacock|2011}}{{sfn|Bosworth|1968|p=35}} In 1062, Abu'l-Aswar received a delegation from the [[Emirate of Tiflis]], an isolated Muslim stronghold within the Christian Georgian kingdoms. Following the death of Emir Ja'far ibn Ali, the locals had evicted his quarrelling sons, and now asked Abu'l-Aswar to assume control of the city. The Shaddadid ruler was inclined to accept, but his [[vizier]], Bakhtiyar ibn Salman, dissuaded him by warning that such an action would disperse his limited forces. After Abu'l-Aswar's refusal, Tiflis was occupied by the Georgians, until they were evicted by Alp Arslan in 1068.{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|pp=19–20, 56–58}} This event highlighted the limitations of Shaddadid power,{{sfn|Peacock|2011}} which was further demonstrated by an [[Alans|Alan]] invasion through the [[Darial Pass]] in the same year: more than 20,000 inhabitants of Arran were carried off as slaves according to Münejjim Bashi's account. In response to the Alan threat, Abu'l-Aswar built a wall and moat around the suburb (''rabad'') of his capital Ganja.{{sfn|Peacock|2011}}{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|p=20}} The gates installed by Abu'l-Aswar for this new fortification were carried off by the Georgians under [[Demetrius I of Georgia|Demetrius I]] in 1139, and are still preserved at the [[Gelati Monastery]] in modern [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|p=31 (note 14)}} In 2012–14, replicas of the original gates were installed in Ganja's Museum of Archaeology and Ethnography.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://en.president.az/articles/10855 | title = Ilham Aliyev reviewed the monumental complex Ganja Fortress Gates - the Museum of Archeology and Ethnography | date = 21 January 2014 | accessdate = 9 October 2015 | publisher = Official website of the President of Azerbaijan }}</ref>

At the same time, Abu'l-Aswar's relations with his neighbour, [[Shirvanshah]] [[Fariburz I]] ({{reign|1063|1069}}), abruptly deteriorated. The two dynasties were linked by family ties—Fariburz's predecessor, [[Sallar of Shirvan|Sallar]] ({{reign|1050|1063}}), had even been married to a daughter of Abu'l-Aswar—but now the Shaddadid ruler launched a series of invasions against [[Shirvan]]. In spring 1063, Abu'l-Aswar captured the Quylamiyan castle, marched on to the capital of Shirvan, [[Shamakhi]], defeated the Shirvanshah's forces in battle, plundered their camp, and captured his own daughter, her treasure and retinue. He then withdrew to Arran, but in July returned to Shirvan to raid it. In the next year, he again invaded Shirvan and captured a number of fortresses, while the local Kurdish tribes went over to him. After his return to Ganja, a peace treaty was signed with the Shirvanshah in June/July 1064, whereby Abu'l-Aswar returned Quylamiyan in exchange for 40,000 [[gold dinar]]s.{{sfn|Minorsky|1977|pp=20–21, 31–32 (notes 15–18), 58}}
{{multiple image|align=left|caption_align=center|header_align=center
